ide range of literary and visual genres, Richard C. Sha examines the shifting economic and aesthetic value of the sketch in sources ranging from auction catalogs and sketching manuals to novels that employed scenes of sketching and courtship. He especially shows how sketching became a double-edged accomplishment for women when used to define "proper" femininity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aArt and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aArtists' preparatory studieszGreat Britain. 0aDescription (Rhetoric)xHistoryy19th century. 0aDrawing, British. 0aEnglish languagey19th centuryxRhetoric. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aRomanticismzGreat Britain. 0aVisual perception in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aArchitecture.  aCultural Studies.  aFine Art.  aGarden History.  aLiterature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Package Archive 1898-1999z978311044252640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978151280736340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781512807363423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781512807363/original  a978-3-11-044252-6  University of Pennsylvania Press Package Archive 1898-1999c1898d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK